column63: Software development of the MH-60S WLT Upgrades (SN1 & SN2).

column39: (333319) Other Commercial and Service Industry Machinery Manufacturing
column45: FULL AND OPEN COMPETITION AFTER EXCLUSION OF SOURCES
column63: CAE will provide modifications to the MH-60S AMT & MH-60R AMT. CAE is responsible for software development of the MH-60R/S AMT Upgrades to include the following scope of effort: Reconfigure the MH-60S AMT architecture to match the MH-60R AMT. Update the baseline for MH-60S specific systems. Update the baseline for AOP 86.X for both device types. Update the Virtual Test sets to the latest in use. Update Information Assurance (IA) compliance. Add five additional malfunctions for both device types, as defined by the customer. Software Engineering Environment (SEE) modification and testing.

column39: (541712) Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Biotechnology)
column63: This subawardee is responsible to support the PRB by performing the following functions:1.  Establish an animal model of ascending intrauterine infection.2.  Study the effect of bacterial products and bacteria on pattern recognition receptors, inflammatory cytokines, chemokines, and antimicrobial peptides by the uterine cervix. 3.  Study the mechanisms whereby exposure in microbial products may lead to preterm labor and/or cervical ripening.4.  Study the effect of progesterone blockade on innate immunity of the uterine cervix.4.  Study the effect of viral infection on the systemic and lower genital tract immune response.

column59: The Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory
column63: This subawardee is responsible to support the PRB by performing the following functions:1.  Synthesis of Cy5-labeled dendrimers.2.  Characterize the biodistribution of dendrimer-Cy5 in the fetus following administration into the amniotic fluid in endotoxin-exposed pregnant rabbits.Data from these studies will be helpful in determining whether intra-amniotic dendrimer therapies are feasible.

column57: OneSAF I2S
column63: Provide technical assistance and management support to the Prime Contractor who is required to provide the overarching OneSAF integration, interoperability and support (I2S) efforts to deliver the OneSAF software product to Product Manager OneSAF, the three US Army Modeling and Simulation (M&S)  Domains and the OneSAF User Community.  The OneSAF user community consists of, but is not limited to, other U.S. Army Program Executive Offices (PEOs) and Program Managers (PMs); Training and Doctrine Command (TRADOC) Battle Labs; Research Development and Engineering Centers (RDECs) and agencies; other Services and Joint agencies; foreign countries; non Department of Defense (DoD) government organizations and agencies; academic institutions; and other Co-Developers.  An open systems approach shall be used as the approach for the continuous evolution of the software product. The I2S contractor shall provide the conceptual modeling, architectural, engineering and software development support required to enhance the OneSAF product line, software product and correct deficiencies identified by the OneSAF Community. The I2S contractor shall, with Governments concurrence, accept, modify, integrate and test handover packages and new capabilities in support of the requirement of the OneSAF program, Production contract and OneSAF User Community. The I2S Contractor shall provide life-cycle sustainment of the released versions, provide maintenance updates, provide on-site support, training and support to the OneSAF Community both in the Continental U.S. (CONUS) and outside of Continental U.S. (OCONUS). The I2S contractor shall conduct the final acceptance and test activities required to deliver the annual, minor and tailored version releases and patches to support research, analysis, training and user requirements in the Integrated Development Environment (IDE).

column63: Provide technical assistance and management support as required to provide the overarching OneSAF integration, interoperability and support (I2S) efforts to deliver the technical assistance and management support to the Prime Contractor who is required to provide the overarching OneSAF integration, interoperability and support (I2S) efforts to deliver the OneSAF software product to Product Manager OneSAF, the three US Army Modeling and Simulation (M&S) Domains and the OneSAF User Community. The OneSAF user community consists of, but is not limited to, other U.S. Army Program Executive Offices (PEOs) and Program Managers (PMs); Training and Doctrine Command (TRADOC) Battle Labs; Research Development and Engineering Centers (RDECs) and agencies; other Services and Joint agencies; foreign countries; non Department of Defense (DoD) government organizations and agencies; Academic institutions; and other Co-Developers. An open systems approach shall be used as the approach for the continuous evolution of the software product. The I2S contractor shall provide the conceptual modeling, architectural, engineering and software development support required to enhance the OneSAF product line, software product and correct deficiencies identified by the OneSAF Community. The I2S contractor shall, with Government's concurrence, accept, modify, integrate and test handover packages and new capabilities in support of the requirement of the OneSAF Program, Production contract and OneSAF User Community. The I2S Contractor shall provide life-cycle sustainment of the released versions, provide maintenance updates, provide on-site support, training and support to the OneSAF Community both in the Continental U.S. (CONUS) and outside of Continental U.S. (OCONUS). The I2S contractor shall conduct the final acceptance and test activities required to deliver the annual, minor and tailored version releases and patches to support research, analysis, training and user requirements in the Integrated Development Environment (IDE).

The scope of this PWS is focused on the definition, design, development, prototype, testing and deployment of JTE capabilities in support of the warfighter.  The scope of this PWS is in supporting the continued deployment and use of JTE ver. 0.6; the development, testing and use of JTE ver 0.8; and the gap analysis, concept development, design, development and testing of JTE ver. 1.0.  These RDTE efforts will include developing and incorporating new hardware, software and emerging technologies and ideas to support training in a broad range of military and non-military operations, at various resolutions of fidelity.  The JTE includes the legacy live, virtual and constructive modes and simulations that are currently a part of the legacy Joint LVC environment.
